Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C. Chop the @new potatoes{1} into 2cm bite-sized pieces (no need to peel). Trim the stalky tops from the @green beans{1}. Pick the @tarragon{1} leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks).

Place the potatoes on a lined #baking tray{} and drizzle over a little @olive oil{}. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a few grinds of @black pepper{a few grinds}. Toss to coat, then spread out evenly and roast on the top shelf of your #oven{} until crispy, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Lay a @British chicken breasts{2} on a #chopping board{}, place your hand flat on top and slice into it from the side. Open it up like a book. This is called butterflying! Repeat with the remaining chicken. Lay the chicken between two sheets of #clingfilm{} and bash it with a #rolling pin{} or the base of a #pan{} until it is 1cm thick. Don't forget to wash your hands afterwards!

Bring a large #saucepan{} of water with a pinch of @salt{pinch} to the boil for the green beans. Heat a splash of @olive oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Season the chicken on both sides with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}. Once the oil is hot, fry the chicken for ~{4-6%minutes} on each side, then remove the pan from the heat.

> The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Add the green beans to your pan of boiling water. Boil until tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Once cooked, drain the beans in a #colander{} and set aside.

Meanwhile, put the #frying pan{} with your chicken in, back on medium heat. Add the @creme fraiche{1}, a splash of @water{} and the @Dijon mustard{20}. Bubble gently until you have the consistency of double cream, then remove from the heat and stir in the tarragon.

> TIP: If you don't like tarragon, add a little less! Serve the roasted new potatoes and the green beans with the chicken on top and a healthy spoonful of your tarragon sauce. Enjoy!